	title = {Generating {CNC} Code from a Domain Specific Language},
	abstract = {Computerized Numeric Control ({CNC}) is an industrial language for the manufacturing of products. {CNC} programs are series of code that
consist of assembler-like instructions and, consequently, they are low-level programs that require specialized developers in order to gain
productivity in programs writing.
In this work we introduce a domain specific language for the generation of {CNC} programs. The {DSL} itself has been developed in Curry, a declarative functional-logic language. Our {DSL} includes a set of
functions that encapsulate {CNC} instructions raising the abstraction level, and therefore, improving productivity. It is designed in such a way that non-expert users can write {CNC} programs. We show how the use of a {DSL} allows us to perform the requirements capture of {CNC} systems and to reduce the gap between the requirements and the
prototype. Finally, from our domain specific language we generate real {CNC} code in order to produce real world applications.},
